All four infected HCoVs in this community have been well adapted to humans and are generally less likely to mutate and cause highly pathogenic diseases, although accidents do occur for unknown reasons as there are rare cases of the more harmful subtype of HCoV-NL63, which has recently been reported to have caused severe lower respiratory tract infections in China.
Generally speaking, when this HCoV acquires the ability to spread efficiently and to remain continuously in the human body, the virus also becomes less harmful or pathogenic.
MERS-CoV was first isolated in 2012 from the lungs of a 60-year-old patient with acute pneumonia and kidney failure in Saudi Arabia.
